# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: virtual-texturing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] In computer graphics, **clipmapping** is a method of clipping a mipmap to a subset of data pertinent to the geometry being displayed.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] The technique was introduced by Christopher C.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] Jones as a "virtual mipmap" for caching arbitrarily large textures in finite physical memory for real-time rendering.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] This is useful for loading as little data as possible when memory is limited, such as on a graphics processing unit.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] For terrain rendering, the idea was adapted into geometry clipmaps, which use nested regular grids centered on the viewer and update them incrementally as the viewpoint moves.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] The technique is used for LODing in NVIDIA’s implementation of voxel cone tracing.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] The high-resolution levels of the mipmapped scene representation are clipped to a region near the camera, while lower resolution levels are clipped further away.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] MegaTexture is a clipmap implementation developed by id Software.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] It was introduced in their id Tech 4 engine and also appeared in id Tech 5 and id Tech 6 before being removed in id Tech 7.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] MegaTexture is a texture allocation technique that uses a single, extremely large texture rather than repeating multiple smaller textures.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] It is also featured in Splash Damage's game *Enemy Territory: Quake Wars*, and was developed by id Software former technical director John Carmack.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] MegaTexture employs a single large texture space for static terrain.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] The texture is stored on removable media or a computer's hard drive and streamed as needed, allowing large amounts of detail and variation over a large area with comparatively little RAM usage.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] Depending on the pixel resolution per square meter, covering a large area could require several gigabytes of memory.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] However, RAM is also filled by the rest of the game and the underlying operating system, limiting the amount available for texturing.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] As the player moves around the game, different sections of the MegaTexture are loaded into memory.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] They are then scaled to the correct size and applied to the 3D models of the terrain.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] Id has presented a more advanced technique that builds upon the MegaTexture idea and virtualizes both the geometry and the textures to obtain unique geometry down to the equivalent of the texel: the sparse voxel octree (SVO).
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] It works by raycasting the geometry represented by voxels (instead of triangles) stored in an octree.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] The geometric detail that can be obtained using this method is nearly infinite, which removes the need for faking 3-dimensional details with techniques such as normal mapping.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] Despite that most voxel rendering tests use very large amounts of memory (up to several GB), Jon Olick of id Software claimed the technology is able to compress such SVO to 1.15 bits per voxel of position data.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] Unlike clipmaps, which clip each mip level around a viewpoint-dependent clipcenter and therefore work best for terrain, virtual texturing preprocesses texture data into equally sized tiles that can be streamed for arbitrary textured geometry.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] *Rage*, powered by the id Tech 5 engine, uses a more advanced technique called virtual texturing.
[src:virtual-texturing/clipmap] Textures can measure up to 128000×128000 pixels and are also used for in-game models and sprites, etc. and not just the terrain.
[src:virtual-texturing/depth-map] In 3D computer graphics and computer vision, a **depth map** is an image or image channel that contains information relating to the distance of the surfaces of scene objects from a viewpoint.
[src:virtual-texturing/depth-map] The term is related (and may be analogous) to *depth buffer*, *Z-buffer*, *Z-buffering*, and *Z-depth*.
[src:virtual-texturing/depth-map] The "Z" in these latter terms relates to a convention that the central axis of view of a camera is in the direction of the camera's Z axis, and not to the absolute Z axis of a scene.
[src:virtual-texturing/depth-map] Two different depth maps can be seen here, together with the original model from which they are derived.
[src:virtual-texturing/depth-map] The first depth map shows luminance in proportion to the distance from the camera.
[src:virtual-texturing/depth-map] Nearer surfaces are darker; further surfaces are lighter.
[src:virtual-texturing/depth-map] The second depth map shows luminance in relation to the distances from a nominal focal plane.
[src:virtual-texturing/depth-map] Surfaces closer to the focal plane are darker; surfaces further from the focal plane are lighter, (both closer to and also further away from the viewpoint).
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Microtexture (MiTx) is the collaborative term for a material's crystallographic parameters and other aspects of microstructure: such as morphology, including size and shape distributions; chemical composition; and crystal orientation and relationships.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Macrotexture (MaTx) is partly a desired property and partly an undesired property.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Short MaTx waves, about 5 mm, act as acoustical pores and reduce tyre/road noise.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] On the other hand, long wave MaTx increase noise.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] MaTx provide wet road friction, especially at high speeds.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Excessive MaTx increases rolling resistance and thus fuel consumption and CO2 emission, contributing to global warming.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Proper roads have MaTx of about 1 mm Mean Profile Depth.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Macrotexture is a family of wave-shaped road surface characteristics.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] While vehicle suspension deflection and dynamic tyre loads are affected by longer waves (roughness), road texture affects the interaction between the road surface and the tyre footprint.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Macrotexture has wavelengths from 0.5 mm up to 50 mm.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Road agencies monitor macrotexture using measurements taken with highway speed laser or inertial profilometers.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Megatexture (MeTx) is a result of pavement wear and distress, causing noise and vibration.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Megatexture has wavelengths from 50 mm up to 500 mm.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Some examples of road damages with much MeTx are potholes, washboards (common on dirt roads) and uneven frost heaves.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] MeTx below 0.2 mm Root-Mean-Square is considered normal on proper roads.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] MaTx and MeTx are measured with laser/inertial profilographs.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Since MiTx has so short waves, it is preferably measured by dry friction brake tests rather than by profiling.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Profilographs that record texture in both left and right wheel paths can be used to identify road sections with hazardous split friction.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] The **profilograph** is a device used to measure pavement surface roughness.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] In the early 20th century, profilographs were low speed rolling devices (for example rolling straight-edges).
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Today, many profilographs are advanced high speed systems with a laser based height sensor in combination with an inertial system that creates a large scale reference plane.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] It is used by construction crews or certified consultants to measure the roughness of in-service road networks, as well as before and after milling off ridges and paving overlays.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Modern profilographs are fully computerized instruments.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] The data collected by a profilograph is used to calculate the International Roughness Index (IRI), which is expressed in units of inches/mile or mm/m.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] IRI values range from 0 (equivalent to driving on a plate of glass) upwards to several hundred in/mile (a very rough road).
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] The IRI value is used for road management to monitor road safety and quality issues.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Many road profilographs are also measuring the pavements cross slope, curvature, longitudinal gradient and rutting.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Some profilographs take digital photos or videos while profiling the road.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Most profilographs also record the position, using GPS technology.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Yet another common measurement option is cracks.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Some profilograph systems include a ground penetrating radar, used to record asphalt layer thickness.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Another type of profilograph system is for measuring the surface texture of a road and how it relates to the coefficient of friction and thus to skid resistance.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Pavement texture is divided into three categories; megatexture, macrotexture, and microtexture.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Microtexture cannot currently be measured directly, except in a laboratory.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Megatexture is measured using a similar profiling method as when obtaining IRI values, while macrotexture is the measurement of the individual variations of the road within a small interval of a few centimeters.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] For example, a road which has gravel spread on top followed by an asphalt seal coat will have a high macrotexture, and a road built with concrete slabs will have low macrotexture.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] For this reason, concrete is often grooved or roughed up immediately after it is laid on the road bed to increase the friction between the tire and road.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Equipment to measure macrotexture currently consists of a distance measuring laser with an extremely small spot size (< 1 mm) and data acquisition systems capable of recording elevations spaced at 1 mm or less.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] The sample rate is generally over 32 kHz.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Macrotexture data can be used to calculate the speed-dependent part of friction between typical car tires and the road surface in both dry and wet conditions.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Lateral friction and cross slope are the key reaction forces acting to keep a cornering vehicle in steady lateral position, while it is subject to exiting forces arising from speed and curvature.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Cross slope and curvature can be measured with a road profilograph, and in combination with friction-related measurements can be used to identify improperly banked curves, which can increase the risk of motor vehicle accidents.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] The inertial compensation makes the profile data more or less independent of what speed the profilometer vehicle had during the measurements, with the assumption that the vehicle does not make large speed variations and the speed is kept above 25 km/h or 15 mph.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] The profilometer system collects data at normal highway speeds, sampling the surface elevations at intervals of 2–15 cm (1–6 in), and requires a high speed data acquisition system capable of obtaining measurements in the kilohertz range.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] The data collected by a profilometer is used to calculate the International Roughness Index (IRI) which is expressed in units of inches/mile or mm/m.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] IRI values range from 0 (equivalent to driving on a plate of glass) upwards to several hundred in/mi (a very rough road).
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Many road profilers also measure the pavement's cross slope, curvature, longitudinal gradient and rutting.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Some profilers take digital photos or videos while profiling the road.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Most profilers also record the position, using GPS technology.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Another quite common measurement option is cracks.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Some profilometer systems include a ground penetrating radar, used to record asphalt layer thickness.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Another type of profilometer is for measuring the surface texture of a road and how it relates to the coefficient of friction and thus to skid resistance.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Pavement texture is divided into three categories: megatexture, macrotexture, and microtexture.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Equipment to measure macrotexture currently consists of a distance measuring laser with an extremely small spot size (< 1 mm) and data acquisition systems capable of recording elevations spaced at a mm or less apart.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Macrotexture data can be used to calculate the speed-depending part of the friction number between typical car tires and the road surface.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] The macrotexture also give information on the difference between dry and wet road friction.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] However, macrotexture cannot be used to calculate a relevant friction number, since also microtexture affects the friction.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Lateral friction and cross slope are the key reaction forces acting to keep a cornering vehicle in steady lateral position, while exposed to exciting forces from speed and curvature.
[src:virtual-texturing/megatexture] Since friction is strongly dependent on macrotexture and texture, cross slope as well as curvature can be measured with a road profiler, so road profilers are very useful to identify improperly banked curves that may pose a risk to motor vehicles.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] In computer graphics, a **mipmap** (*mip* being an acronym of the Latin phrase *multum in parvo*, meaning "much in little") is a pre-calculated, optimized sequence of images, each of which has an image resolution which is a factor of two smaller than the previous.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] They are intended to increase rendering speed and reduce aliasing artifacts.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] A high-resolution mipmap image is used for high-density samples, such as for objects close to the camera; lower-resolution images are used as the object appears farther away.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] This is a more efficient way of downscaling a texture than sampling all texels in the original texture that would contribute to a screen pixel; it is faster to take a constant number of samples from the appropriately downfiltered textures.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] Since mipmaps, by definition, are pre-allocated, additional storage space is required to take advantage of them.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] They are also related to wavelet compression.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] Mipmaps are widely used in 3D computer games, flight simulators, other 3D imaging systems for texture filtering, and 2D and 3D GIS software.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] Mipmap textures are used in 3D scenes to decrease the time required to render a scene.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] They also improve image quality by reducing aliasing and Moiré patterns that occur at large viewing distances, at the cost of 33% more memory per texture.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] Mipmapping was invented by Lance Williams in 1983 and is described in his paper *Pyramidal parametrics*.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] From the abstract: "This paper advances a 'pyramidal parametric' prefiltering and sampling geometry which minimizes aliasing effects and assures continuity within and between target images." The referenced pyramid can be imagined as the set of mipmaps stacked in front of each other.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] The first patent issued on Mipmap and texture generation was in 1983 by Johnson Yan, Nicholas Szabo, and Lish-Yann Chen of Link Flight Simulation (Singer).
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] Using their approach, texture could be generated and superimposed on surfaces (curvilinear and planar) of any orientation and could be done in real-time.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] Texture patterns could be modeled suggestive of the real world material they were intended to represent in a continuous way and free of aliasing, ultimately providing level of detail and gradual (imperceptible) detail level transitions.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] Texture generating became repeatable and coherent from frame to frame and remained in correct perspective and appropriate occultation.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] The origin of the term mipmap is an initialism of the Latin phrase *multum in parvo* ("much in little"), and map, modeled on bitmap.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] The term *pyramids* is still commonly used in a GIS context.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] In GIS software, pyramids are primarily used for speeding up rendering times.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] Each bitmap image of the mipmap set is a downsized duplicate of the main texture, but at a certain reduced level of detail.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] Rendering speed increases since the number of texture pixels (*texels*) being processed per display pixel can be much lower for similar results with the simpler mipmap textures.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] If using a limited number of texture samples per display pixel (as is the case with bilinear filtering) then artifacts are reduced since the mipmap images are effectively already anti-aliased.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] Scaling down and up is made more efficient with mipmaps as well.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] If the texture has a basic size of 256 by 256 pixels, then the associated mipmap set may contain a series of 8 images, each one-fourth the total area of the previous one: 128×128 pixels, 64×64, 32×32, 16×16, 8×8, 4×4, 2×2, 1×1 (a single pixel).
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] If, for example, a scene is rendering this texture in a space of 40×40 pixels, then either a scaled-up version of the 32×32 (without trilinear interpolation) or an interpolation of the 64×64 and the 32×32 mipmaps (with trilinear interpolation) would be used.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] The simplest way to generate these textures is by successive averaging; however, more sophisticated algorithms (perhaps based on signal processing and Fourier transforms) can also be used.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] Showing each color channel of each level of an RGB mipmap as a separate plane (left) demonstrates that the whole mipmap forms a square of 4 times the area.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] The increase in storage space required for all of these mipmaps is a third of the original texture, because the sum of the areas 1/4 + 1/16 + 1/64 + 1/256 + ⋯ converges to 1/3.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] This is the inspiration for the tag *multum in parvo*.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] When a texture is viewed at a steep angle, the filtering should not be uniform in each direction (it should be anisotropic rather than isotropic), and a compromise resolution is required.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] If a higher resolution is used, the cache coherence goes down, and the aliasing is increased in one direction, but the image tends to be clearer.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] If a lower resolution is used, the cache coherence is improved, but the image is overly blurry.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] This would be a tradeoff of MIP level of detail (LOD) for aliasing vs blurriness.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] However anisotropic filtering attempts to resolve this trade-off by sampling a non isotropic texture footprint for each pixel rather than merely adjusting the MIP LOD.
[src:virtual-texturing/mipmap] This non isotropic texture sampling requires either a more sophisticated storage scheme or a summation of more texture fetches at higher frequencies.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] A *texture map* refers to a 2D image ("texture") that adds visual detail to a 3D model.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The image can be stored as a raster graphic.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The coordinate space that converts from a 3D model's 3D space into a 2D space for sampling from the texture map is variously called *UV space*, *UV coordinates*, or *texture space*.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The UV Coordinates are used to read the color from the texture and apply it to the pixel.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The original technique was pioneered by Edwin Catmull in 1974 as part of his doctoral thesis.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Texture mapping originally referred to *diffuse mapping*, a method that simply mapped pixels from a texture to a 3D surface ("wrapping" the image around the object).
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] A **texture map** is an image applied ("mapped") to the surface of a shape or polygon.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] This may be a bitmap image or a procedural texture.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] They may be stored in common image file formats, referenced by 3D model formats or material definitions, and assembled into resource bundles.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] They may have one to three dimensions, although two dimensions are most common for visible surfaces.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] For use with modern hardware, texture map data may be stored in swizzled or tiled orderings to improve cache coherency.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Rendering APIs typically manage texture map resources (which may be located in device memory) as buffers or surfaces, and may allow 'render to texture' for additional effects such as post processing or environment mapping.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Texture maps usually contain RGB color data (either stored as direct color, compressed formats, or indexed color), and sometimes an additional channel for alpha blending (RGBA) especially for billboards and decal overlay textures.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] It is possible to use the alpha channel (which may be convenient to store in formats parsed by hardware) for other uses such as specularity.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Multiple texture maps (or channels) may be combined for control over specularity, normals, displacement, or subsurface scattering, e.g. for skin rendering.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Multiple texture images may be combined in texture atlases or array textures to reduce state changes for modern hardware.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] (They may be considered a modern evolution of tile map graphics).
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Modern hardware often supports cube map textures with multiple faces for environment mapping.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Texture maps may be acquired by scanning or digital photography, designed in image manipulation software such as GIMP or Photoshop, or painted onto 3D surfaces directly in a 3D paint tool such as Mudbox or ZBrush.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] This process is akin to applying patterned paper to a plain white box.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Every vertex in a polygon is assigned a texture coordinate (which in the 2D case is also known as UV coordinates).
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] This may be done through explicit assignment of vertex attributes, manually edited in a 3D modelling package through UV unwrapping tools.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] It is also possible to associate a procedural transformation from 3D space to texture space with the material.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] This might be accomplished via planar projection or, alternatively, cylindrical or spherical mapping.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] More complex mappings may consider the distance along a surface to minimize distortion.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] These coordinates are interpolated across the faces of polygons to sample the texture map during rendering.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Textures may be repeated or mirrored to extend a finite rectangular bitmap over a larger area, or they may have a one-to-one unique "injective" mapping from every piece of a surface (which is important for render mapping and light mapping, also known as baking).
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Texture mapping maps the model surface (or screen space during rasterization) into *texture space*; in this space, the texture map is visible in its undistorted form.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] UV unwrapping tools typically provide a view in texture space for manual editing of texture coordinates.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Some rendering techniques such as subsurface scattering may be performed approximately by texture-space operations.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Multitexturing is the use of more than one texture at a time on a polygon.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] For instance, a light map texture may be used to light a surface as an alternative to recalculating that lighting every time the surface is rendered.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] *Microtextures* or *detail textures* are used to add higher frequency details, and *dirt maps* add weathering and variation; this can greatly reduce the apparent periodicity of repeating textures.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Modern graphics may use more than 10 layers, which are combined using shaders, for greater fidelity.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Bump mapping has become popular in video games, as graphics hardware has become powerful enough to accommodate it in real-time.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The way that samples (e.g. when viewed as pixels on the screen) are calculated from the texels (texture pixels) is governed by texture filtering.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The cheapest method is to use the nearest-neighbour interpolation, but bilinear interpolation or trilinear interpolation between mipmaps are two commonly used alternatives which reduce aliasing or jaggies.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] In the event of a texture coordinate being outside the texture, it is either clamped or wrapped.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Anisotropic filtering better eliminates directional artefacts when viewing textures from oblique viewing angles.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Texture streaming is a means of using data streams for textures, where each texture is available in two or more different resolutions, as to determine which texture should be loaded into memory and used based on draw distance from the viewer and how much memory is available for textures.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Texture streaming allows a rendering engine to use low resolution textures for objects far away from the viewer's camera, and resolve those into more detailed textures, read from a data source, as the point of view nears the objects.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] As an optimization, it is possible to render detail from a complex, high-resolution model or expensive process (such as global illumination) into a surface texture (possibly on a low-resolution model).
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] This technique is called *baking* (or *render mapping*) and is most commonly used for light maps, but may also be used to generate normal maps and displacement maps.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The original *Quake* software engine used on-the-fly baking to combine light maps and colour maps in a process called *surface caching*.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Baking can be used as a form of level of detail generation, where a complex scene with many different elements and materials may be approximated by a single element with a single texture, which is then algorithmically reduced for lower rendering cost and fewer drawcalls.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] It is also used to take high-detail models from 3D sculpting software and point cloud scanning and approximate them with meshes more suitable for realtime rendering.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Various techniques have evolved in software and hardware implementations.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Each offers different trade-offs in precision, versatility, and performance.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] In contrast to perpendicular polygons, this leads to noticeable distortion with perspective transformations (as shown in the figure: the checker box texture appears bent), especially as primitives near the camera.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] This distortion can be reduced by subdividing polygons into smaller polygons.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Using quad primitives for rectangular objects can look less incorrect than if those rectangles were split into triangles.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] However, since interpolating four points adds complexity to the rasterization, most early implementations preferred triangles only.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Some hardware, such as the forward texture mapping used by the Nvidia NV1, offered efficient quad primitives.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] With perspective correction, triangles become equivalent to quad primitives and this advantage disappears.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] For rectangular objects that are at right angles to the viewer (like floors and walls), the perspective only needs to be corrected in one direction across the screen rather than both.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The correct perspective mapping can be calculated at the left and right edges of the floor.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Affine linear interpolation across that horizontal span will look correct because every pixel along that line is the same distance from the viewer.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] In contrast, the original z , u , and v , before the division, are not linear across the surface in screen space.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] It is therefore possible to linearly interpolate these reciprocals across the surface, computing corrected values at each pixel, to produce a perspective correct texture mapping.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] To do this, the reciprocals at each vertex of the geometry (three points for a triangle) are calculated.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Then, linear interpolation can be done on these reciprocals between the n vertices (e.g., using barycentric coordinates), resulting in interpolated values across the surface.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] However, as our division by z altered their coordinate system, this $u_{i},v_{i}$ cannot be used as texture coordinates.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] To correct back to the $u,v$ space, the corrected z is calculated by taking the reciprocal once again: $z_{correct}={\frac {1}{\frac {1}{z_{i}}}}$ .
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] This correction makes it so that the difference from pixel to pixel between texture coordinates is smaller in parts of the polygon that are closer to the viewer (stretching the texture wider) and is larger in parts that are farther away (compressing the texture).
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Affine texture mapping directly interpolates a texture coordinate $u_{\alpha }$ between two endpoints $u_{0}$ and $u_{1}$ : $u_{\alpha }=(1-\alpha )u_{0}+\alpha u_{1}$ where $0\leq \alpha \leq 1$ .
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Various techniques have evolved for rendering texture mapped geometry into images with different quality and precision trade-offs, which can be applied to both software and hardware.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Classic software texture mappers generally only performed simple texture mapping with one lighting effect at most (typically applied through a lookup table), and the perspective correctness was about 16 times more expensive.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The *Doom* engine restricted the world to vertical walls and horizontal floors and ceilings, with a camera that could only rotate about the vertical axis.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] This meant the walls would be a constant depth coordinate along a vertical line and the floors and ceilings would have a constant depth along a horizontal line.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] After performing one perspective correction calculation for the depth, the rest of the line could use fast affine mapping.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Some later renderers of this era simulated a small amount of camera pitch with shearing which allowed the appearance of greater freedom while using the same rendering technique.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Some engines were able to render texture mapped heightmaps (e.g.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Nova Logic's Voxel Space, and the engine for *Outcast*) via Bresenham-like incremental algorithms, producing the appearance of a texture mapped landscape without the use of traditional geometric primitives.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Every triangle can be further subdivided into groups of about 16 pixels in order to achieve two goals: keeping the arithmetic mill busy at all times and producing faster arithmetic results.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] For perspective texture mapping without hardware support, a triangle is broken down into smaller triangles for rendering and affine mapping is used on them.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The reason this technique works is that the distortion of affine mapping becomes much less noticeable on smaller polygons.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The Sony PlayStation made extensive use of this because it only supported affine mapping in hardware and had a relatively high triangle throughput compared to its peers.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Software renderers generally prefer screen subdivision because it has less overhead.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Additionally, they try to do linear interpolation along a line of pixels to simplify the set-up (compared to 2D affine interpolation), thus lessening the overhead further.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Another reason is that affine texture mapping does not fit into the low number of CPU registers of the x86 CPU; the 68000 and RISC processors are much more suited for that approach.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] As the polygons are rendered independently, it may be possible to switch between spans and columns or diagonal directions depending on the orientation of the polygon normal to achieve a more constant z, but the effort seems not to be worth it.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] One other technique is to approximate the perspective with a faster calculation, such as a polynomial.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] A second uses the ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{z_{i}}}}$ value of the last two drawn pixels to linearly extrapolate the next value.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] For the latter, the division is then done starting from those values so that all that has to be divided is a small remainder.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] However, the amount of bookkeeping needed makes this technique too slow on most systems.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] A third technique, used by the Build Engine (used, most notably, in *Duke Nukem 3D*), builds on the constant distance trick used by the *Doom* engine by finding and rendering along the line of constant distance for arbitrary polygons.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Texture mapping hardware was originally developed for simulation (e.g. as implemented in the Evans and Sutherland ESIG and Singer-Link Digital Image Generators DIG) and professional graphics workstations (such as Silicon Graphics) and broadcast digital video effects machines such as the Ampex ADO.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Texture mapping hardware later appeared in arcade cabinets, consumer video game consoles, and PC video cards in the mid-1990s.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] In flight simulations, texture mapping provided important motion and altitude cues necessary for pilot training not available on untextured surfaces.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Additionally, texture mapping was implemented so that real-time processing of prefiltered texture patterns stored in memory could be accessed by the video processor in real-time.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Modern graphics processing units (GPUs) provide specialised fixed function units called *texture samplers*, or *texture mapping units*, to perform texture mapping, usually with trilinear filtering or better multi-tap anisotropic filtering and hardware for decoding specific formats such as DXTn.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] As of 2016, texture mapping hardware is ubiquitous as most SOCs contain a suitable GPU.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Some hardware implementations combine texture mapping with hidden-surface determination in tile-based deferred rendering or scanline rendering; such systems only fetch the visible texels at the expense of using greater workspace for transformed vertices.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Most systems have settled on the z-buffering approach, which can still reduce the texture mapping workload with front-to-back sorting.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Inverse texture mapping instead iterates through pixels on the screen and decides what texel to use for each.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Of these methods, inverse texture mapping has become standard in modern hardware.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] With this method, a pixel on the screen is mapped to a point on the texture.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Each vertex of a rendering primitive is projected to a point on the screen, and each of these points is mapped to a u,v texel coordinate on the texture.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] A rasterizer will interpolate between these points to fill in each pixel covered by the primitive.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The primary advantage of this method is that each pixel covered by a primitive will be traversed exactly once.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Once a primitive's vertices are transformed, the amount of remaining work scales directly with how many pixels it covers on the screen.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The main disadvantage is that the memory access pattern in the texture space will not be linear if the texture is at an angle to the screen.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] This disadvantage is often addressed by texture caching techniques, such as the swizzled texture memory arrangement.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The linear interpolation can be used directly for simple and efficient affine texture mapping, but can also be adapted for perspective correctness.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Forward texture mapping maps each texel of the texture to a pixel on the screen.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] After transforming a rectangular primitive to a place on the screen, a forward texture mapping renderer iterates through each texel on the texture, splatting each one onto a pixel of the frame buffer.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] This was used by some hardware, such as the 3DO, the Sega Saturn and the NV1.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The primary advantage is that the texture will be accessed in a simple linear order, allowing very efficient caching of the texture data.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] However, this benefit is also its disadvantage: as a primitive gets smaller on screen, it still has to iterate over every texel in the texture, causing many pixels to be overdrawn redundantly.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] This method is also well suited for rendering quad primitives rather than reducing them to triangles, which provided an advantage when perspective correct texturing was not available in hardware.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] This is because the affine distortion of a quad looks less incorrect than the same quad split into two triangles .
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] The NV1 hardware also allowed a quadratic interpolation mode to provide an even better approximation of perspective correctness.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] UV mapping became an important technique for 3D modelling and assisted in clipping the texture correctly when the primitive went past the edge of the screen, but existing hardware did not provide effective implementations of this.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] These shortcomings could have been addressed with further development, but GPU design has mostly shifted toward using the inverse mapping technique.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] It is possible to use texture mapping hardware to accelerate both the reconstruction of voxel data sets from tomographic scans, and to visualize the results.
[src:virtual-texturing/texture-mapping] Many user interfaces use texture mapping to accelerate animated transitions of screen elements, e.g.
